03970nam a22006855i 9789815104028DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20232023si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898151040287 a10.1355/97898151040282doi  a(DE-B1597)651063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0440002bisacsh1 aMartinus, Melinda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe EU’s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM) :bImplications for ASEAN-EU Relations /cMelinda Martinus, Kanin Laopirun. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (40 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tThe EU’s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM): Implications for ASEAN-EU Relations -- tThe EU’s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM): Implications for ASEAN-EU Relations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a growing policy trend that in addressing climate change, various trade measures must be implemented to enhance the sustainable practices of global stakeholders. As a response to level up the playing field of global trade partners in enhancing sustainability, the EU recently introduced the European Union (EU) Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (CBAM), which will impose a carbon price on certain imports, namely, electricity, aluminium, cement, iron and steel, and fertilizer, to the EU. The EU CBAM may, however, cause trade disputes among World Trade Organization (WTO) members. EU and ASEAN trade relations are currently on an upswing trajectory, and there are therefore some risks involved in implementing the EU CBAM in the ASEAN region. At the same time, despite the perceived adverse effects, there is room for improvement in communicating EU CBAM implementation in ASEAN. The EU should introduce more calibrated approaches to implementing the EU CBAM in ASEAN, particularly considering the political and strategic risks, economic development and capacity, and climate ambitions of individual ASEAN countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCarbon taxeszEuropean Union countries. 0aClimatic changesxGovernment policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aLaopirun, Kanin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLaopirun, Kanin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinus, Melinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981510402840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815104028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815104028/original  a978-3-11-117804-2  DG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2b2023  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK